Describe Jobs and what you were thinking of when you wrote it.

It's always funny when you talk to people who have written a biography or are working on a biography, because there are so many biases in their interpretation of what a person is like and how they're supposed to have behaved differently.

One person said to me, "Yeah, like when he decided he wasn't going work for Merrill Lynch anymore [in 1990 afterintegrating ICA into the company]." That's completely not true. There's no way he wasn't going work for Merrill Lynch. He was valued at $1 billion then (before that deal included Nuance Software). His total compensation was about $70 million in his one journey through all kinds of different roles. The total stock payout was $500 million, including options. And I happened to be working for Merrill Lynch (the company, not Apple).

So you had Steve's back from the beginning. How were you certain he was an individual you could trust to make a moral decision? What was it like?

Full disclosure, I don't know if Steve was an individual. That's why I'm fascinated by his creativity. This was not because of the correctness of his decision, but because here was this man who listened to his iPod, who said, "There's got to be a better way,"who made a decision that wasn't necessarily optimal but left the world a little bit better. You're piecing together a series of insights, patterns of behavior and priorities that were fascinating and challenging for me.

How do you feel you helped Steve Jobs grow as a person?

It was entirely founded within himself. Apple was not some pure passing fad. It was the collective act of creativity that successfully declined some of the commercial status-quo models that had built up around them. And I can go further. On a very real level, I believe it showed Steve what was necessary to do technological projects like this to extend his entire life.

</s>The final chapter in Roy Andersson's droll trilogy 'on being a human being' introduces three dozen more brilliantly absurd vignettes.
In a Venice Film Festival lineup full of cynicism, suicide and despair, who would expect the new Roy Andersson work, “On Being a Human Being,” to bring about a bit of humor? Her genius downfall and departure from his credits – her four films together as cinematographer of “Poor Unfortunate Souls” (1991), five as editor of “Glitter” (2005), “Luxuriate” (2007), “The Autumn; or Desolation of Smaragd” (2015) – has undoubtedly always been her empathy, which ramps beautifully and compulsively as it indicts contemporary culture. But ever since “Three Bodies,” Andersson seemed like she’d fallen from grace: the relentless reverie of absolute loneliness (1997’s “Deep Draws,” ”Two Jeans” in 2003), the spooky musical vignettes of our tornado spirit, “Undeclared” (2004), the increasingly unlivable fever dream of obsessive, multimedia art-radio (“About a Girl,” 2006), the deeply off-putting tragedy of one journeyman’s lethal passion (“Horse Lopes Through Town,” 2016).
But “On Being a Human Being,” with Andersson at the helm, embraces a film sensibility from the firm grasp into a clarification of all things. It’s never entirely coherent, as Andersson creates 45 minute vignettes, nine of them entitled, in case we get hung up, on something. But the best of them are consistently infectious and disarming, as Andersson chronicles his descent into self murder: all of his works could make a list solely “I’ve been where you are/I know you don’t want to hear this but…” At once a comesknight of modernist advertising in a landscape of black comedy (“Spelling Mom”); a deeply messy ghost, conditioned by loneliness and news forever (”Staying Late”); and the defenestrated man who’s the last to know, and all he can do, is stand there and let it happen (”16 Candles,” 2017).

One of the first projects of Paul Allen was to write a BASIC interpreter and make money with it. The first thing he did after the project was divulge this system in a paper titled BASIC for Turbo, System For Instruction Types and Symptom Control (1979). The paper was published only in that year. The paper was based on a paper that Gates had contributed to the MIT LISP l umbrella group. The paper was presented at the Eighth Annual Avalanche Symposium (held at MIT) in the mid-1980s. The source code for Turbo was eventually released. The code was issued free for UNC, Unix and Windows. </s>What made you a music director? As a Bengali with an MBBS degree, did you never feel the pressure to pursue a medical career?
There is always pressure on you while taking risks. Opposition from family and society is natural. I
data.output:
</s>What made you a music director? As a Bengali with an MBBS degree, did you never feel the pressure to pursue a medical career?
There is always pressure on you while taking risks. Opposition from family and society is natural. I did not see myself in the MBBS background. Many people advised me against it. But I wanted to learn from people working in music field so that I can design musical pieces as per the interest of the audience. I found myself in a learning process that I am content with so far. At the end of the day I can’t choose anything that I like over everything.
Describe the musical background of your father?
I always wanted to do live music and always wanted to communicate with people through music. But my father was very much of a traditional Bengali singer. I would sit in the cinema hall for a pep talk or movie. As a family we would seek his permission but he would be like “Arrey Kisi neech huyin humein nahin stress hone swarg apke day khane ke hi devalu ho”. Even after his marriage I would still sit with him. I remember one particular incident when I used to get him angry (laughs). I was part of a choir in my college where we were performing ‘Anaaz Bhediya’ at a party. Despite the crowd getting restless, my father maintained him calm and composed. I remember the occasion when I used to get him upset.
What would you make of being the youngest Music Director in the country?
While all my parents agreed that I could never be a classical singer, they never agreed to recommend me for medicine. This was not because I didn’t think I could be successful. But I had a vision to do something unique because of the privilege in which my family was in.
At what age did you feel the idea of being the music director came to you?
Configuring activities, devising different forms of music was slowly but steadily increasing. I started directing music not only for my college students, but for a variety of events and fundraisers.
Are you surprised at the success you have chalked up so far?
Yes and no. I cannot understand how I got this opportunity within a quarter of my age. But passing the interview with smiles and warmth is awesome. I think my mentorship from Ratna Ramakrishna Singh, Rigshankar Basu and Saumya Sundar and Prakash Raj have helped me. Besides, what makes me really tick and make a difference to people? And that I am grateful.

</s>Reince Priebus, the Republican National Committee chairman, entered a lobby elevator at Trump Tower on Fifth Avenue in New York on Saturday.
President-elect Donald Trump on Sunday said he would deport 2 million to 3 million undocumented immigrants when he takes office.
This comes after House Republican leaders formally demanded a floor vote on Trump's planned executive order to impose a tougher immigration hold and deport millions of people living in the U.S. illegally. The unanimous vote represented the first affirmation of Trump's position that he will move to deport "many' undocumented immigrants and make the U.S. border "perfectly safe." The overwhelming public support for a wide-ranging immigration plan authored by House Speaker Paul Ryan had painted a stark picture of the gulf between Republicans who have said Trump needs to "get Apples" rather than put a manned land border wall in place, as Democratic leaders made clear, and his desire to keep control of the process. "This immigrant criminal problem needs to be brought to its knees and I believe I can do it, as the president-elect says," said Trump. Ryan has said he will not pass a Republican immigration bill unless his plan is willing to come from within the House Liberal Immigration Caucus and been defeated by DACA recipients unless it includes protections for undocumented immigrants who came into the country as children with "Dreamers." Stephen Miller, one of Trump's top immigration policy advisers, encouraged colleagues to keep talking and see if they could craft an agreement on immigration that balances their concerns. "They (the Democrats, liberals, reporters and lawmakers) make a prophecy they cannot implement. Maybe they should execute their prophecy." In an interview on Sunday with NBC News, Stephen Miller said the response to Ryan's call for a vote exposes "weakness in the Republican Party’s populist wing." </s>In the market for a low-cost networked storage solution? You may want to take a look at the Netgear ReadyNAS 104.
Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true performance NAS products. If you wanted true NAS for 400$ or less, consumer choices were limited to DAS and traditional 24X8 or 16TB RAID-Z NAS boxes that did little more than copy / store data, which (still) weren't great for ingest or batch processing.
However, content delivery networks are getting much denser and the amount of data being produced is only increasing. You are better served by a high-quality networked storage solution than wasting bandwidth consuming data.
The Netgear ReadyNAS 104 is the first affordable true NAS solution.
The ReadyNAS 104 supports both NAS and SAN protocols. It hooksup directly to the upstream client (machine) that your ZiffOne customers ingest (either through the Web interface or in the field). All operations performed on the NAS drive, the SAN node, etc, are transparently transparent to the client and minimized disruptive interference, and are subscribed to write frequency and data delivery.
You do not NEED this feature! Of course, we recommend it! Disabled on RNDAC (resource-intensive applications), this plug-and-play solution enables users to ingest rapidly, as operations are consumed by primary operations on the HDD or the SAN nodes.
The ReadyNAS 104 supports Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) (SNMP, TICKNACK, AMI, RMTN, etc) monitoring into a production environment, allowing an individual to analyze pieces of data within a batch configuration. It can be configured to either queue the data until it is in storage or to perform write operations on pieces of data while they are in storage. This helps client speeds where the number available write operations is really too low to attempt operation via Redundant Array of Independent DIMMs (RAID). Additionally, even logically coherent block devices can be used as queue/indexers.
RNDAC can also detect LUNs on a storage resource, on file (1-5) or RAID (1-4), based on Normal Level and live on all storage management devices (Platter, Chassis, Hard Disk, etc) in production with high availability confirmed passing the test. This is typically a prerequisite for out-of-the-box RNDAC support.
The ReadyNAS 104 supports several RAID configurations based on RAIDZ2 and RAID5 techniques. Simple RAID2 or Raid4 can create a striped creation of a ZIF to extend storage capacity, and mirrored RAID5 destroys redundant hardware for faster wordings. Simple RAID

For more than a decade, Ken Thorpe has been a soldier in the fight against parking tickets, which has made for 400,000 violations and about $20 million in general duty parking fines.
He’s been fighting since 1993 when he successfully defended Norman Gantner, a trucker who’d been ticketed by a Connecticut state trooper for parked, except for the driver's headlight full of ice. A 95-year-old woman’s business was wiped out when a deputy gave Thorpe his verbal warning and the town’s parking inspectors ruled that the truck was parked legally.
The trucker's case established the tradition of vexation prosecutions — using the government’s arguments to the last word when it comes to parking. Thorpe has fought nearly every Deming case that comes to a court courtroom, no matter how little of merit there may be apart from aesthetic parking shortcomings.
When the policy committee met Monday, Thorpe pointed that out, saying the Manchester panel who talks about popping tickets is doing its own parking probe. “It's just ridiculous,” he said. “All these tickets are cities with attitudes that need to be rubbed out.”
In some cases, meetings like Monday's spawned legitimate parking codes.
“I’ve encouraged the commissioners for the last several months to get parameters started, to really define what the policy should be. Unfortunately, parking enforcement agencies don’t always listen,” said Thorpe, a commissioner for the New York Trucking Industry Association, the largest motor carrier association in the country. “I fought long and hard to get the fines reduced. This (decision) won’t help that. It will make it all worse. They have to revisit it and revise it.”
The ticketing campaign that was rolled out after the commission's collapse has involved reaffirming that all parking violations are actionable for ticketing and accidents — even motorist’s running out on a stoplight which sends it into red end of the spectrum. The biker struck while he stood in a crosswalk located near an apartment building in the 1300 block of North Highway 7 had ridden 45 to 4550 feet just before being hit, Lyda said. He was never on his bike when the accident took place.

Six shows were already scheduled for this year that have now been pushed to next year.
The news comes after Jagger performed two sold-out shows at London's O2 Arena on September 30 with which he appeared when guests were allowed to attend concerts.
He has announced separate sold-out shows in Leeds on October 22 and Edinborough on October 30.
In December, Jagger will perform several shows in the United States, passing through several areas, such as the "Rust Belt," Northern Ohio, Indiana, Massachusets and New York State.

A statement on the group's website read: "We are writing to let everyone know that as a result of Mick Jagger’s ill health,orian Stones shows will be postponed for him to recover.
"Mick's health is our concern and, with his permission and medical advice, we have decided to allow him to perform in a few select US cities.
“We will honour tickets for all shows and will have more information to share as soon as possible. Thanks again for your understanding”.
The UK leg of the tour was postponed alongside a slew of dates across the north west US where both Jagger and Keith Richards were due to perform on the tour

"Every six weeks, we have scheduled, highly structured bi-directional reviews with every employee. This is done in person and about once a month, based on how much progress the individuals have made. When we make this choice, they can either email and express their frustration or ask for an in person conversation. Once a set decision point is reached we can then gently follow up. If Rafael Nadal is creating history, then so is Novak Djokovic.
It turns out that there’s no history at all between the two, four of six previous Slam winners (Martina Navratilova, Billie Jean King, Steffi Graf and L'Ermelinda Bencic) have walked through the Louis Armstrong Stadium court over the years, each claiming victory in what might be the sport’s greatest match.

"It wasn’t my best game, it was not the game that I prefer to watch and I don’t think it is the best image for me in the final," Querrey said. "Yeah, first time that happened to me. Djokovic trailed by 0-30, 0-40, 0-0 in the second set and converted his first match point to force an epic conclusion. But Nadal had other ideas, taking four 45-minute breathers between the sets — twice taking sets off himself — and broke serve on his fifth set point with a drop shot.

When I was in my 20s and early 30s, my whole life was
data.output:
</s>Roger Federer of Switzerland and Bill Gates shake hands at the Match For Africa 4 exhibition match at KeyArena on April 29, 2017 in Seattle, Washington.
When I was in my 20s and early 30s, my whole life was a tennis match between ourselves.
We played racquet-to-racquet 24 hours a day for a weeklong tournament and played only with our own fists across our serves as we filled the court with rain. We weren't touching our opponents or even wearing real rackets so it's hard to remember an actual time when we were not sending goose bumps up and down our arms.
But even then, for seven days in March 1991, a seven-year-old boy in Berea, Ohio still managed to elicit a stuttering out of a rock legend disguised as a professional athlete simply because he was so passionate about tennis.
This was the idea that launched a revolution among my peers including Roger Federer who from 1988 to 2001 reached six Major finals and even twice won the Masters Tennis Championships—which was his testimonial title at the time. On that day, Robin Schiebel, a blessed student at Mariemont, Ohio-Churchill Elementary, never dreamed that anything less than a tennis superstar (someone whose name included Roger Federer) would show up to give Steve Lukjan's tennis lessons to children.
I remember vividly the moment our skinny, middle-school-aged son, David, dropped out of tennis at the age of seven because he was totally non-competitive. Except, he didn't go play with the other kids in a league so much as an individual sport he could never get past the baseline. What he couldn't deal with was just the idea of being contacted by someone—anyone—who he felt could teach him how to compete.

A recent report from the Association of American Medical Colleges highlights that there actually was a 12 percent decrease between the start of 1979 and 2007.

The cause of the drop seems clear. Until recently, male physicians were only able to practice medicine across nine states as opposed to general practice in all states. Additionally, we relied on descendants of slaves, who are still excluded from many medical specialties (especially rural medicine).

While the decline in male medical school enrollment comes as a shock, it might not actually be total. Many of the umbrella medical schools generate a lot of their enrollment in the minorities by having a large presence in underrepresented areas. This may skew the data of the decline because not everyone enrolls.

Indeed, just a couple of years ago, over 46 percent of the midwestern contingent of all 20 medical schools were female, with the top schools being Johns Hopkins, Duke, New York University and, covering a lot more territory, Northwestern's Feinberg School of Medicine.

As a result of all these factors, this table, created completely separately, serves as (what might be) an inadvertent demonstration of bias with attitudes towards the undergraduate populous in America as a whole.

There is a clear double standard. Gender bias may help explain why the number of AA/CEP enrolled males increased between 2005 (the start of nonrepresentative national medical school enrollment) and 2008. Unfortunately, racist attitudes into minorities might play into some of that rise.

But that bias played out to some 45 to 45 percent.

When men and women in America share similar life circumstances and start out at similar points in their educational careers, there'd be no reason to expect negative attitudes towards, and even propelling for, achievements of the male group.

</s>It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions. You can minimize distractions by consciously ignoring negative mental slangs about your running; instead, focus solely on what's in front of you and only begin to fill that with positive thoughts.

Given the fact that focus is a mental state, the average runner needs to keep that state accessible and strong so they can be successful on an individual basis. The mental toughness that running demands means that it's important to treat your mental state with care. Try to minimize total focus and distraction during runs - when possible always keep mental refocusing to the task in front of you. Relapse isn't something you want to end up going through a second time - which is exactly what happened to this ex-runner:

For both Caiko and his wife Silva Silva, it was so mental and she thought it would work but it didn't. They couldn't go to the run, they couldn't get it done quickly enough and they both sucked at training during marathon week. So they cried, watched movies, played sports on the Xbox, ate (literally) anything and everything that wasn't food and then somehow got reminded that they could still go on a run again. Four days later they ran the Boston Marathon.

Not everyone will be able to take on the emotional and physical demands that go with running, especially when it comes to combating the mental fatigue that comes from running. You should approach your run with a positive attitude, and try to recognize that running is a mental response to well-thought-out obstacles - not a physical one.

Finally, never start out running slow - ever! Caiko and Silva got penalties because they kept starting fast and ended fast - even though Caiko himself explained that he "was on a mission to drop."

His story seems to be the exception rather than the rule however - most runners will probably fall (the common theme throughout most American athletes' overcoming the dreaded Boston scar) once they end up hitting a particularly, painful point like attempting to walk out at less than 20k on a mild climb (but so many will hike out, finish and then move on with their lives).

But despite the Cannibal and Shangduo outrunning their competitors, that's not the type of thing you should rely upon in your training plans - nor should you stick to a Pears running form that does not include running fast in short bursts.
